<p><b><font size="4">What is HTML? What is XHTML?</font></b></p>
<ul>
  <li>HTML is used to create electronic documents that can be read on many 
  different systems using software called a browser. </li>
  <li>The browser translates the html codes into a presentation on the screen.</li>
  <li>HTML is NOT a true programming language</li>
  <li>HTML is not a WYSIWYG processor or publisher.<br>
  -carriage returns creates only &quot;white space&quot; and that browsers usually 
  compress this white space into a SINGLE space.</li>
  <li>HTML or Hyper Text Markup Language</li>
	<li>XHTML is a simple, more standardized version of HTML. </li>
	<li>XHTML standard is based the rules and philosophy of XML and NOT html 4.x</li>
	<li>E<b>X</b>tensible <b>H</b>yper<b>T</b>ext <b>M</b>arkup <b>L</b>anguage </li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><font size="4">&nbsp;Do you need help or are you just 
browsing?</font></b></p>
<p><b><font size="4">Browsers</font></b></p>
<p>(IE vs <a target="_blank" href="http://www.mozilla.org/">Firefox</a> 
on a PC ) vs (Firefox vs IE vs Safari on a Mac)<br>
&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><font size="4">Lets get started!!</font></b></p>
<p><b><font size="4">Tag you're it! </font></b></p>
<p><b><br>
</b>-Throughout the semester with almost every new concept I introduce I will be 
introducing a new set of tags and attributes to go with it.</p>
<p>A <b>tag (or element) </b>is an html code that is enclosed in angel brackets &lt;&gt;. They are 
used to lay out the web page. The&nbsp; <b>&lt;br/&gt; (empty tag) </b>for example will add a line 
break.</p>
<p>Most tags however are of the <b>container</b> type. These tags have both a 
starting tag and an end tag. For example, if I wanted to bold a word I would 
surround that word with the starting and ending &lt;b&gt; &lt;/b&gt; tag. Notice that the 
end tag is the same as the starting tag but with a &quot;/&quot; placed in front. <br>
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp; &lt;b&gt; HI WORLD &lt;/b&gt; would produce <b>HI WORLD</b> as output on the 
screen.</p>
<p>An <b>attribute</b> is a special code that can enhance or modify a tag. They 
are generally located in the starting tag after the tag name. <br>
<br>
&nbsp;&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt; jkfahljkghadfjhgaouhoaruehgihraeg &lt;/p&gt; would display 
this horrible paragraph to the center of the browser window.</p>
<p>To be compliant with the new html standard (xhtml), all tags and attributes 
must be in lower case. In addition, all values of attributes need to surrounded 
by quotes. Here is the basic syntax for xhtml tags and attributes</p>
<p><b>&lt;tag attribute=&quot;value&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp; &lt;/tag&gt;</b></p>
<p><b>ALL</b> tags need to be closed!&nbsp; <br>
<br>
examples &lt;h1&gt; Hello World &lt;/h1&gt; &lt;br/&gt;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><b><font size="4">OK Now how do I make one of these web pages??</font></b></p>
<p>First you need to pick an application to produce your web page.</p>
<p><b><font size="4">Please, make a &quot;note&quot; of this.....</font></b></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; HTML(text) editor vs. Web editor</p>
<ul>
  <li>Text editor is a plain application that allows you to create, save and 
  modify text. It has some editing features but may not have the full 
  functionality of most word processors. It also doesn't bring some of the 
  problems that comes with a word processor when creating an html page. </li>
  <li>The text editor that we will use it <b>NOTEPAD</b>, yes that NOTEPAD.</li>
  <li>Please do not mistakenly open WORDPAD and confuse this application with 
  NOTEPAD. WordPad is a word processor and will cause problems when creating and 
  html page.</li>
  <li>a <b>WEB editor</b> is a WYSIWYG type of application that we will use 
  later in the semester.</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><b><font size="4">Basic HTML template.</font></b></p>
<p><font size="4"><b>&lt;html&gt;</b></font></p>
<p><font size="4"><b>&lt;head&gt;</b></font></p>
<p><font size="4"><b>&lt;title&gt;&nbsp; &lt;/title&gt;</b></font></p>
<p><font size="4"><b>&lt;/head&gt;</b></font></p>
<p><font size="4"><b>&lt;body&gt;</b></font></p>
<p><font size="4"><b>&lt;/body&gt;<br>
<br>
&lt;/html&gt;</b></font></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<ul>
  <li><font size="4">HTML - Alerts the browser of the presence an html file</font></li>
  <li><font size="4">HEAD<b> - </b>provides description about the document</font></li>
  <li><font size="4">TITLE - Always located in the HEAD. Provides a description 
  about the document for display above the window.</font></li>
  <li><font size="4">BODY - Identifies the contents of the Web page.</font></li>
</ul>
<p><b><font size="4">Creating an XHTML Source Document.</font></b></p>
<p>How do we go from html to xhtml?</p>
<p>Since XHTML is based on XML and NOT HTML, it inherits the syntax rules of 
XML.<br>
One of the primary syntax rules concerning us the case sensitivity.&nbsp; HTML 
is NOT case sensitive, however, XHTML is.&nbsp; ALL XHTML TAGS NEED TO BE IN 
LOWER CASE. </p>
<p><font size="4"><b>Basic XHTML Template.</b></font></p>
<p>Two steps to go from HTML to XHTML</p>
<ol>
	<li>Add the following two cryptic lines BEFORE the &lt;html&gt; tag<br>
<ul> <li>&lt;?xml version=&quot;1.0&quot;?&gt; <br> &lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 
        Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www/w3/org/TR/xhtml/11/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt;</li></ul> </li>
<li>Add the following attribute to the &lt;html&gt; tag<br>
<ul><li> &lt;html xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml&quot;&gt;</li></ul></li>
</ol>
	<p>Other XHTML syntax issues:</p>
<p>All attributes need to be in lower case. Values that these attributes hold 
will be placed AFTER an &quot;=&quot; sign and contained in quotes. </p>
<p>This leaves us with: (page 29-32 in book)</p>
<p><font size="4"><b>&lt;?xml version=&quot;1.0&quot;?&gt; </b></font></p>
<p><font size="4"><b>&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 
	Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www/w3/org/TR/xhtml/11/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt;</b></font></p>
<p><font size="4"><b>&lt;html xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml&quot;&gt;</b></font></p>
<p><font size="4"><b>&lt;head&gt;</b></font></p>
<p><font size="4"><b>&lt;title&gt;&nbsp; &lt;/title&gt;</b></font></p>
<p><font size="4"><b>&lt;/head&gt;</b></font></p>
<p><font size="4"><b>&lt;body&gt;</b></font></p>
<p><font size="4"><b>&lt;/body&gt;<br>
<br>
&lt;/html&gt;</b></font></p>
<p><font size="4"><b>To the tags!</b></font></p>
<p><font size="4"><b>&lt;meta/&gt;</b></font> The meta tag is used to specify Keywords 
that describe a documents contents as well as a short description.</p>
<p>Two necessary attributes. &quot;name&quot; &amp; &quot;content&quot;</p>
<p>&lt;meta name=&quot;keywords&quot; content=&quot;baseball, soccer, tennis&quot;/&gt;<br>
&lt;meta name=&quot;&quot;description&quot; content=&quot;Sports information page&quot;/&gt;</p>
<p><b>&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</b> The paragraph tag. Used so separate text within a web page. 
Container type. Will provide line breaks.</p>
<p>Key attribute : align.</p>
<p>&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;</p>
<p><font size="4"><b>&lt;br/&gt;</b></font> used for line break</p>
<p><font size="4"><b>Headings</b></font></p>
<p><font size="4"><b>&lt;h1&gt;</b></font> Header one<font size="4"><b> &lt;/h1&gt;</b></font><br>
<font size="4"><b>&lt;h2&gt;</b></font> Header two <font size="4"><b>&lt;/h2&gt;</b></font><br>
<font size="4"><b>&lt;h3&gt;</b></font> Header three <font size="4"><b>&lt;/h3&gt;</b></font><br>
<font size="4"><b>&lt;h4&gt; </b></font>Header four <font size="4"><b>&lt;/h4&gt;</b></font><br>
<font size="4"><b>&lt;h5&gt;</b></font> Header five <font size="4"><b>&lt;/h5&gt;</b></font><br>
<font size="4"><b>&lt;h6&gt;</b></font> Header six <font size="4"><b>&lt;/h6&gt;</b></font></p>
<p><b>&lt;em&gt;<i> </i></b><i>italics</i><b> &lt;/em&gt;</b></p>
<p><b>&lt;strong&gt; bold&nbsp; &lt;/strong&gt;</b></p>
<p><b>&lt;font&gt; &lt;/font&gt; </b>(not supported in XHTML Strict) </p>
<p>Key attributes: size, face, color.</p>
